# ⚙️ Automation with Maven — CI/CD Fundamentals

A hands-on implementation of build automation and CI/CD fundamentals using Apache Maven with the PetClinic Java application. Followed structured learning material and ran the full pipeline end-to-end independently.

---

## 📌 What This Project Covers

This project walks through automating the **build, test, and deployment** lifecycle of a Java application using Maven — a core skill in any DevOps/CI/CD workflow.

---

## 🔧 Tech Stack

| Tool | Role |
|---|---|
| **Java** | Application language (Spring PetClinic) |
| **Apache Maven** | Build automation & dependency management |
| **Git** | Version control |
| **CI/CD Concepts** | Pipeline structure & automation principles |

---

## 🚀 What Was Implemented

- ✅ Set up Maven project structure with `pom.xml` configuration
- ✅ Automated dependency management using Maven Central
- ✅ Ran build lifecycle phases: `validate → compile → test → package`
- ✅ Generated build artifacts (`.jar` / `.war`)
- ✅ Understood how Maven integrates into CI/CD pipelines (Jenkins, GitHub Actions)

---

## 📋 How to Run

### Prerequisites
- Java JDK 11+
- Apache Maven 3.6+
- Git

### Steps

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/i-am-monika/automation-with-maven.git
cd automation-with-maven

# Compile the project
mvn compile

# Run tests
mvn test

# Package into a JAR/WAR
mvn package

# Full clean build
mvn clean install
```

---

## 📂 Maven Build Lifecycle

```
validate → initialize → compile → test → package → verify → install → deploy
```

This project focuses on the `compile → test → package` stages as the core of a CI pipeline.

---

## 🚀 What I Learned

- How Maven manages dependencies and build lifecycles
- The role of `pom.xml` in project configuration
- How build tools like Maven plug into Jenkins/GitHub Actions pipelines
- Practical understanding of artifact generation for deployment

